comment: Lemma for ~ kur14 : main proof. The set ` T ` here contains all the distinct combinations of ` k ` and ` c ` that can arise, and we prove here that applying ` k ` or ` c ` to any element of ` T ` yields another elemnt of ` T ` . In operator shorthand, we have ` T = { A , c A , k A ` ` , c k A , k c A , c k c A , k c k A , c k c k A , k c k c A , ` ` c k c k c A , k c k c k A , c k c k c k A , k c k c k c A , ` ` c k c k c k c A } ` . From the identities ` c c A = A ` and ` k k A = k A ` , we can reduce any operator combination containing two adjacent identical operators, which is why the list only contains alternating sequences. The reason the sequences don't keep going after a certain point is due to the identity ` k c k A = k c k c k c k A ` , proved in ~ kur14lem6 . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 11-Feb-2015.)
